For each document, based on their unique document ID, we collected all click data (usage) until 2019. We then computed the Spearman correlation between the usage and the citations. We chose Spearman correlation because the data, like all citation data, does not have a normal distribution. The results show a Spearman correlation of 0.57 (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p< 0.0001$$\end{document}). This means that there is a moderate positive correlation between citations and usage, which is highly significant.
